04187nam a22005655i 9780822394754DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20112012ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223947547 a10.1515/97808223947542doi  a(DE-B1597)554173  a(OCoLC)1058622211  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aHIS0240002bisacsh04a302.2/2440982231 aRappaport, Joanne, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBeyond the Lettered City :bIndigenous Literacies in the Andes /cTom Cummins, Joanne Rappaport. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2011] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (396 p.) :b58 b&w illustrations, 2 charts, 9 color plates  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNarrating Native Histories00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbout The Series -- tList Of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Imagining Colonial Culture -- t2. Genre/Gender/Género: "Que no es uno ni otro, ni está claro" -- t3. The Indigenous Lettered City -- t4. Genres in Action -- t5. The King's Quillca and the Rituality of Literacy -- t6. Reorienting the Colonial Body: Space and the Imposition of Literacy -- tConclusion -- tGlossary -- tNotes -- tReferences Cited -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Beyond the Lettered City, the anthropologist Joanne Rappaport and the art historian Tom Cummins examine the colonial imposition of alphabetic and visual literacy on indigenous groups in the northern Andes. They consider how the Andean peoples received, maintained, and subverted the conventions of Spanish literacy, often combining them with their own traditions. Indigenous Andean communities neither used narrative pictorial representation nor had alphabetic or hieroglyphic literacy before the arrival of the Spaniards. To absorb the conventions of Spanish literacy, they had to engage with European symbolic systems. Doing so altered their worldviews and everyday lives, making alphabetic and visual literacy prime tools of colonial domination. Rappaport and Cummins advocate a broad understanding of literacy, including not only reading and writing, but also interpretations of the spoken word, paintings, wax seals, gestures, and urban design. By analyzing secular and religious notarial manuals and dictionaries, urban architecture, religious images, catechisms and sermons, and the vast corpus of administrative documents produced by the colonial authorities and indigenous scribes, they expand Ángel Rama's concept of the lettered city to encompass many of those who previously would have been considered the least literate.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aCommunication and culturezAndes RegionxHistory. 0aIndians of South AmericazAndes RegionxHistory. 0aLiteracyxSocial aspectszAndes RegionxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / General.2bisacsh1 aCummins, Tom, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822394754zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822394754423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822394754.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles